   {:e #blake3 "b30ba95e68a0ab241136295c770fe39a4454f9c7af1fda8aabac9c6ff0f486cf" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "LIVESTORE WRITE-TX ROOT CAUSE (Session 039): Transaction::commit() validates datoms against the CURRENT schema. When a txn file contains datoms for attributes registered in a different txn (e.g., :exploration/body registered in the full_schema txn, used in an observation txn), commit() rejects them as unknown. This is correct for user-facing validation but incorrect for internal replay of persisted txn files. The fix is Option D: Store needs a pub fn apply_datoms(&mut self, datoms: &[Datom]) method that inserts datoms + updates all 6 indexes + MaterializedViews WITHOUT schema validation. This is exactly the loop at Store::genesis() lines 958-986, factored out as a public incremental method. This also fixes a pre-existing bug in load_store()'s incremental path (layout.rs line 460) where the same commit() failure causes silent stale-store returns. ADDITIONALLY: The silent Err(_) in write_tx was a design error. Error handling should NEVER silently ignore failures — either propagate or guarantee success.; Session entity: :recon/trace-9f133b2cbaee7f2e; LIVESTORE-4 DISCOVERY: main.rs has 2 code paths that create their own DiskLayout and call write_tx with invalidate_cache, deleting store.bin: (1) ST-1 auto-session-start (lines 112-127) runs BEFORE status, (2) T2-1 post-command path (line 148+) runs AFTER status. These delete the store.bin that LiveStore wrote via flush/drop. The write-through IS working correctly inside status.rs, but main.rs still uses the old invalidate-on-write pattern. This is exactly what LIVESTORE-5a (command dispatch migration) fixes — creating ONE LiveStore at process start and passing it to all phases. Until 5a, the cache benefit of write-through is negated by the main.rs invalidations.; Session entity: :recon/trace-8486867a01159731; Session entity: :task/t-ab65c62c; SESSION 039 CLOSE: VERIFICATION RESULTS. (1) Production store (75,111 datoms) works correctly with new binary — 3.0s status, all data visible. (2) INIT DATOM COUNT DISCREPANCY: new binary init produces 4,927 datoms vs old binary's 15,208. Difference is ~10K datoms across 2 fewer transactions. Most likely cause: the old init bootstrapped spec elements from the spec/ directory and/or wrote the full schema transaction, which the new LiveStore-based init may be silently failing on (apply_datoms handles the data but the init code paths that generate the bootstrap txns may have borrow issues from the 5c agent's migration). The store IS functional — observe/status/harvest all work. But fewer bootstrap datoms means fewer spec elements, potentially affecting F(S) and bilateral scores on fresh stores. PRIORITY: Investigate in Session 040 before LIVESTORE-5d. (3) SESSION METRICS: 97s->3.0s (32x perf), 1744 tests, 11 commits, 14 tasks, 4 spec elements, 6 observations, Store::apply_datoms as foundational kernel primitive.; Session entity: :task/t-468595d8; Session entity: :recon/trace-f1114b310d9e2058; SESSION 039 ARCHITECTURAL LESSONS. (1) SILENT FAILURES ARE THE WORST BUG CLASS. The Err(_) arm in write_tx that silently ignored commit failures caused cascading invisible data loss. Rule: NEVER silently ignore errors in write paths. Either propagate or guarantee success. (2) WHEN SOMETHING FAILS, ASK WHY THE WORKING PATH WORKS. The fix for write_tx was already in from_datoms — the holistic reconstruction pattern that bypasses schema validation. I should have read from_datoms first, not after three wrong attempts. (3) MECHANICAL CHANGES NEED MECHANICAL TOOLS. Using sed/perl for &store->store was error-prone. cargo clippy --fix handles this correctly. (4) THE INCREMENTAL MONOID FOLD REQUIRES A DIFFERENT VALIDATION MODEL. User-facing writes validate (Transaction::commit). Internal replay doesn't (Store::apply_datoms). These are different operations with different trust boundaries. Conflating them caused the schema bootstrap bug. (5) SPEC GAPS ARE REAL BUGS. The absence of ADR-STORE-011 (incremental replay without validation) meant the system had no formal guidance for how to replay persisted transactions. The gap led to the buggy commit()-based incremental path in load_store (POLICY-6).; Session entity: :recon/trace-9021112ab9660747; Session entity: :task/t-2e9bbe23; Session entity: :task/t-9ca466d5; Session entity: :recon/trace-16c797d7d0bd37d2; Session entity: :task/t-8f681308\nEvery Command as Transaction" :op :assert}
